{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17499779","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17499779"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:02:58+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:02:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1542"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1542","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1542"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.03,0.08,0.39,0.44]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1542"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"91348"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1542","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1542"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1542"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75097"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2366"},{"type":"contributions","id":"29392"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31245"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42336"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45697"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"91348","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/91348"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a 12-hour history of severe upper abdominal pain radiating to his back. He describes the pain as an ache that has steadily worsened. He has also experienced extreme nausea, vomiting twice, and diarrhoea over the same period. He tried some home remedies without relief. He has states he drank \u0027a fair bit\u0027 at a buck\u0027s party two days prior. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 110/min and regular, blood pressure 120/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 38.1\u00b0C. Abdominal examination reveals tenderness maximal in the epigastrium, with guarding and distension. An erythematous rash in a net-like pattern is noted across his abdomen (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely explanation for the skin changes shown?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Herpes zoster infection","Allergy to a contact dressing","Streptococcal cellulitis","Hot water bottle application","Retroperitoneal extravasation of blood"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe skin changes shown in the image are characteristic of erythema ab igne, a condition caused by repeated exposure to heat. In this case, the most likely explanation is the application of a \u003Cstrong\u003Ehot water bottle\u003C/strong\u003E. The patient, suffering from what appears to be acute pancreatitis (given the severe upper abdominal pain radiating to the back, nausea, vomiting, and recent alcohol consumption), likely used a hot water bottle or heat pack to alleviate his symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHerpes zoster infection\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents as a painful, unilateral, vesicular rash that follows a dermatomal distribution. The reticulated pattern and distribution seen here is not consistent with herpes zoster rash.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eallergy to a contact dressing\u003C/strong\u003E would typically cause a more uniform erythematous reaction in the shape of the dressing, not the reticulated pattern seen here. Additionally, there\u0027s no mention of any dressing application in the patient\u0027s history.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStreptococcal cellulitis\u003C/strong\u003E usually presents as a diffuse, erythematous, warm, and tender area of skin. It doesn\u0027t typically have the reticulated pattern seen in this image.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERetroperitoneal extravasation of blood\u003C/strong\u003E can cause skin discoloration, but it typically appears as bruising (ecchymosis) rather than the reticulated erythema seen here. It\u0027s also usually associated with trauma or anticoagulation, neither of which are mentioned in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EErythema ab igne is characterised by a localised area of reticulated erythema that develops after repeated application of heat. It\u0027s often seen in patients with chronic pain who use heat for symptom relief from heaters, water bottles or wheat bags. In this acute presentation, the patient likely applied a hot water bottle repeatedly over a short period to manage his severe abdominal pain. With chronic exposure, these areas can develop hyperpigmentation. Recognition of this pattern can be a clue to underlying pain conditions that the patient may be self-treating with heat application.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Erythema ab igne is a cutaneous reaction to recurrent direct heat exposure.","Erythema ab igne presents as a reticulated, erythematous rash in areas of chronic heat application.","Erythema ab igne can be a clue to underlying chronic pain conditions."],"references":["Kettelhut EA, Traylor J, Roach JP. Erythema Ab Igne. [Updated 2020 Aug 10]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2021 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK538250/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75097"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1542"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"17774"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"17774","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/17774"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/7fbe02f0-59ea-4dd5-a791-0a3bbaaaaa7c.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/7fbe02f0-59ea-4dd5-a791-0a3bbaaaaa7c.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75097","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/75097"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-15T17:40:23+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-15T17:49:34+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1542"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"91348"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"sel